\par\par \b \uc2  RI  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  strong, yet risks loom. \b0\par\par\uc2 694 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Significant risks loom over Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , despite its strong fundamentals, because the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  may worsen, deregulation has lost momentum and core inflation is still high, the World Bank warns. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank said in its latest annual report on Indonesia that the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  performed very well last year with 7.8 percent growth, its inflation dropping to 6.6 percent and domestic and foreign investments remaining buoyant. \par \par \uc2  "Despite this strong performance, significant risks remain," warns the report, Indonesia sustaining high growth with equity, which was issued here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  The report praises Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as responsible even in the run-up to the election and its prudent foreign borrowings as well debt management. \par \par \uc2  But, the higher oil earnings were not fully sterilized by an increased \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus and off-\b \highlight22\uc2 budget spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  looks less contractionary, it warns. \par \par \uc2  It noted that the deregulation drive has slowed and even reversed in some areas. There has been slippage in scheduled \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts and domestic regulations continue to hurt efficiency and inter-island equity. \par \par \uc2  "About 800 of the announced \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts were not implemented on schedule," the report said. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank praised the lifting of the ban on imports of used fishing ships but said the measure was immediately followed by costly local content regulations. \par \par \uc2  It said a lack of transparency and competition had hurt performance in sectors such as infrastructure and natural resource development. \par \par \uc2  "Ad hoc interventions (which are on the rise) and other common local practices are coming under increasing global scrutiny," the report cautions. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank, the coordinator of Indonesia's creditor consortium - the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) - warned that unless momentum was restored to deregulation, Indonesia risks slower growth and deteriorating equity. \par \par \uc2  The report also addressed the issues of invisible business costs and good governance. \par \par \uc2  "Only modest improvements have been made in the complex web of domestic restrictions, fees and levies," the report said. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank warned there was a widely-held perception that the invisible costs of doing business in Indonesia were very high. \par \par \uc2  It quoted a survey by Japan's External Trade Organization in 1995 which concluded that 50 percent of Japanese firms operating in the county cited complexity of administrative procedures as the most difficult problem faced by their businesses. \par \par \uc2  "Without effective institutions and good governance, businesses can have their competitive position adversely affected by the selective imposition of regulations, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and laws," it said. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank said that credibility of \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the consistency with which rules were enforced and property rights protected had an important effect on the level and pattern of investment. \par \par \uc2  It quoted the findings of surveys of businessmen which gave Indonesia high marks for criteria such as little risk of expropriation with no compensation but low marks for bureaucratic delays and contract enforceability. \par \par \uc2  "Such factors increase \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and risk. They favor the well connected over the efficient and they inflate costs. They engender cynicism and the perception of unfairness," it said. \par \par \uc2  The report said that these perceptions had not impeded growth or foreign investment in recent years. Nonetheless, to keep pace with other successful countries, Indonesia will need to address this issue sooner or later. \par \par \uc2  Ports \par \par \uc2  The World Bank called for serious attention to seaport delays and the problems caused by new regulations and bureaucratic obstructionism in sea transport. \par \par \uc2  It also suggested that the customs performance be subject to independent evaluation to ensure that import flows remain as smooth as before April when the country used a pre-shipment inspection system to clear imports. \par \par \uc2  "If there is a deterioration (in customs service), it is essential that action is taken quickly to restore quality service, otherwise opportunities for growth and employment expansion will be forfeited by increased costs of imported inputs," it warned. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank reminded CGI that despite the increased role of private-sector financing, official foreign assistance would continue to be important for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, " a level of commitments from the CGI roughly similar to last year (US$5.26 billion) would be very supportive," the World Bank suggested. (vin) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dt6j004q4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
