\par\par \b \uc2  Govt to hold seminar on corruption next month. \b0\par\par\uc2 640 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 June 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government is to invite ministers, scholars and critics to speak in a seminar on bureaucracy next month to delve deeply into the problem of corruption. \par \par \uc2  State Minister of Administrative Reforms T.B. Silalahi said yesterday the government would use the speakers' criticism and suggestions to improve the performance of civil servants to make a clean and efficient government. The seminar will be held from July 7 to July 9. \par \par \uc2  "The strongest criticism against the bureaucracy is focused on corruption and we want to get input for improvements," Silalahi said after meeting President Soeharto at the Bina Graha presidential office. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi said the seminar would examine ways to prepare the bureaucracy for free trade and look at civil servants as the "pioneers of development". \par \par \uc2  "Our development achievements are widely recognized by other countries," the minister quoted Soeharto as saying. \par \par \uc2  The seminar's speakers will include State Minister of National Development Planning Ginandjar Kartasasmita; Minister of Defense and Security Gen. (ret) Edi Sudradjat; outspoken economist Sjahrir; the University of Indonesia's Faculty of Economics' dean, Dorojatun Kuntjoro-Jakti; and senior journalist Ninok Leksono. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia had 4,044,703 civil servants in August 1995, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi reiterated that it was impossible to eradicate corruption because it was common throughout the world, even in industrialized countries like the United States. \par \par \uc2  "It is clear that we cannot completely eradicate corruption, we can only minimize it, otherwise heaven would be overcrowded," Silalahi said and burst into laughter. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank's latest annual report on Indonesia says the civil service should have a salary structure which rewards merit and honesty, credible penalties for malfeasance, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms to reduce the discretionary authority of government officials and greater accountability for poor performance or abuse of power. \par \par \uc2  "The World Bank's international experience suggests that improved governance will depend on widespread local support and commitment at all levels both in terms of leadership and action," says the report, Indonesia sustaining high growth with equity, which was issued Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  The issues of rampant corruption and poor \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  service were commonly raised by campaigners before last month's general election. \par \par \uc2  The report points out that surveys consistently rank Indonesia low on "bureaucratic delays" and "contract enforceability". \par \par \uc2  "Such factors increase \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and risk. They favor the well-connected over the efficient. They inflate costs. They engender cynicism and perceptions of unfairness," the report says. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi dismissed the view that higher salaries would automatically reduce corruption by citing well-paid officials who became corrupt because they wanted more expensive possessions. \par \par \uc2  On Tuesday, Silalahi said that corruption was by no means monopolized by government officials. "The amount of corruption in the private sector is more horrifying than in government offices." \par \par \uc2  But he said yesterday that Indonesia's laws and regulations on corruption were most likely the most comprehensive in the world, and that even a mouse could not escape their trap. \par \par \uc2  Outspoken economist Didik J. Rachbini said in April that corruption in Indonesia had become an acute disease that would take a long time to heal. \par \par \uc2  "We have had an anti-corruption law since the 1970s. But it is a toothless tiger," he said. \par \par \uc2  A 1996 survey, by the Hong Kong-based Politics and \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Risk Consultancy, disclosed that Indonesia ranked third among the 12 most corrupt Asian countries. China was first and Vietnam second. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi also talked to Soeharto about Harmoko's new position as state minister of special assignments. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi said that Harmoko, who is expected to relinquish the post before assuming a seat in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  next October, would need less staff and facilities than other ministers. \par \par \uc2  "This position is just temporary but we will evaluate what he needs to carry out his duties," he said. (06) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dt6k004qf\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
