\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah and stock market continue to gain ground. \b0\par\par\uc2 615 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 August 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The rupiah surged yesterday by another 100 points against the U.S. dollar and stock prices increased 1.67 percent. \par \par \uc2  Foreign exchange dealers said spot rupiah, which opened at 2,780/2,810, strengthened and broke the resistance level of 2,700 to 2,650 in morning trading and closed at 2,670/2,690. \par \par \uc2  One local foreign exchange bank dealer said the current tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had forced local players to sell their dollar to meet their rupiah obligations. \par \par \uc2  "Trading is quite big today with several local banks selling dollar to back up their rupiah liquidity," said one local foreign exchange bank dealer. \par \par \uc2  He said the government's efforts to stabilize the rupiah through the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had borne fruit. \par \par \uc2  "I salute the government's success in stabilizing rupiah. It proves that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals are really good," the dealer said. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Finance Saleh Afiff said yesterday the government had achieved its first target to bring rupiah below the upper level of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) now defunct intervention band (Rp 2,378-2,682 against the U.S. dollar). \par \par \uc2  "We have been successful in forcing the rupiah to cross below the upper level of the defunct intervention band. And we foresee that the rupiah will continue to strengthen," Afiff told journalists. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah fell to an historic low of 3,045 against the greenback after the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  floated the rupiah last week in the wake of sustained speculative attacks on regional currencies. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah started recovering following the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's shock increase of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  Tuesday. It doubled one-week \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Certificates (SBI) to 20 percent, 2 to 22 percent, one-month to 30 percent and 3 to 28 percent. \par \par \uc2  Afiff reiterated yesterday that the government would continue to tighten rupiah for some time until market jitters calmed down and the rupiah stabilized. \par \par \uc2  Businessman Sofyan Wanandi yesterday urged the government to gradually ease the tight rupiah liquidity to give businesses a chance to breathe. \par \par \uc2  Sofyan said most businesspeople did not know what to do with their businesses as rupiah remained tight. \par \par \uc2  "Businesspeople are confused and have lost direction as they don't know when the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will end. Consequently, many of them have entered the frenzy to take benefit of the situation," Sofyan said. \par \par \uc2  He suggested the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  gradually cut their SBI rates and supply rupiah bit by bit to signal to businesses that the tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would end soon. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, share prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange ended higher yesterday as the strengthening of the rupiah boosted sentiment, stock brokers said. \par \par \uc2  But news that Standard & Poor's downgraded outlook for some of the country's largest banks pared some gains, they added. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta composite index again broke the 600 level, jumping 9.89 points, or 1.67 percent, to close at 603.06 points. \par \par \uc2  Advancers led decliners by 103 to 34 with 50 stocks unchanged. \par \par \uc2  Total turnover was 451.08 million shares, valued at Rp 1.07 trillion (US$399 million). \par \par \uc2  ANZ Securities' head of research, Tom Soulsby, said the increase was a result of "bottom fishing" from investors as they saw many good stocks were already very cheap. \par \par \uc2  "Foreign investors have returned today and have been active buying good value stocks," Soulsby said. \par \par \uc2  He said many share prices were already undervalued as the overall market had declined by 35 percent in dollar terms during the last three weeks. \par \par \uc2  But he warned the stock market would continue to be volatile as long as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the currency market remained. (jsk/rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dt8m006r1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
