\par\par \b \uc2  RI foreign  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\uc2  proves durable. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Rizal Sukma. \par \uc2 960 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 September 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles on Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  which was first inducted on Sept. 2, 1948. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): President Soeharto sees the use of foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a function of domestic politics directed toward achieving national interests which are largely defined in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. \par \par \uc2  As early as 1969, Soeharto stated: "We shall only be able to play an effective role if we ourselves possess a great national vitality." \par \par \uc2  While the New Order had no intention of moving Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  beyond the framework of bebas-aktif (independent and active), it set for itself the task of returning to the "original" meaning of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  President Soeharto also realized that before Indonesia could pursue the independent-and-active \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there was an inevitable need for putting the house in order (i.e. national development). It was this pragmatic logic that has guided and shaped Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ever since. \par \par \uc2  However, the New Order's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  did not escape criticism. For example, close \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations with the West and Japan were criticized as a violation of the true bebas-aktif principle. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, the prolonged suspension of diplomatic ties with China was seen as evidence that Indonesia had abandoned its commitment to the non-aligned principle. \par \par \uc2  The New Order leadership was also criticized for being "too low profile" and no longer active in foreign affairs. Its foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , however, has demonstrated a clear and concrete manifestation of the bebas-aktif principle as originally defined in terms of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of "no pact." \par \par \uc2  Criticism began to dissipate when, at the end of the 1980s, Indonesia's government indicated its willingness to once again play a more active role in international affairs. After devoting more than two decades of its resources to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development, the New Order government felt that the time had come for Indonesia to play a role commensurate with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  success at home. \par \par \uc2  The New Order began to pursue the principle of bebas-aktif more vigorously by restoring diplomatic ties with China in August 1990, becoming the chair of the Non-Aligned Movement for the period of 1992-1995 and hosting the Asia-Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation (APEC) Summit in November 1994. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, the New Order's commitment to maintaining Indonesia's independence was clearly displayed by its decision to dissolve the Inter-Governmental Group on Indonesia. The government recognized that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aid had been used by donor countries, especially the Netherlands, to interfere in Indonesia's domestic affairs. \par \par \uc2  When Indonesia finalized a "security agreement" with Australia in December 1995, however, questions arouse as to whether the act was a sign that Indonesia had abandoned its bebas-aktif principle altogether or whether it represented the a new interpretation of the principle. \par \par \uc2  Even though the government did not attempt to justify the decision to have a security agreement with Australia, in terms of the bebas-aktif principle, it does not mean that the principle has been abandoned. \par \par \uc2  On the contrary, it can be argued that the government continues to hold the view that the meaning of bebas-aktif, to which it has subscribed for the past three decades, remains as relevant as ever. \par \par \uc2  The decision can also be seen as a display of how, in the government's view, a truly bebas-aktif foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be implemented in accordance with the changing international environment. \par \par \uc2  The decision also registers the rejection by Indonesia to a narrow interpretation of the bebas-aktif \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The 1950s interpretation that the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was a commitment to establishing a balance between the two opposing blocs is obviously no longer relevant since their demise. \par \par \uc2  Nonetheless, the New Order government continues to subscribe to the view of the early 1950s which urges Indonesia to stay out of a military pact. It can also be said that the New Order tends to invoke a broader meaning of bebas-aktif, pragmatic and flexible enough to accommodate whatever actions suit the interests of the state. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, bebas-aktif can also mean that Indonesia is free to make its own decision as to how it can best meet its national interests at any given time. \par \par \uc2  The government's position on this issue, which is no longer constrained by domestic rivalry in making foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is also assisted by how Indonesia's elite have come to view the place of the bebas-aktif principle in foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discourse. \par \par \uc2  The majority, if not all, of Indonesian leaders and elite share the view that the principle of bebas-aktif constitutes one of the principles which serves as a starting point. \par \par \uc2  And, there is a strong consensus among them about the never-changing relevance of this principle. The New Order government, political elite and critics do not consider a change in the guiding principle as necessary, even though they are aware that the international environment has undergone tremendous change since the end of 1980s. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, so strong is the consensus, a deliberate deviation from this principle seems unthinkable. \par \par \uc2  More importantly, security \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the region after the Cold War requires a greater degree of "flexibility" in Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . And, such a flexibility can be attained by making the principle of bebas-aktif itself more flexible. \par \par \uc2  In this regard, the security arrangement with Australia can be interpreted as one expression of Indonesia's attempt to loosen the meaning of bebas-aktif. This opens up the possibility of formalizing security cooperation with other countries. \par \par \uc2  In other words, the conceptual significance of bebas-aktif in Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has not changed. What has changed is the way in which the principle is implemented. \par \par \uc2  The writer is a researcher at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dt93007d2\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
