\par\par \b \uc2  Insolvent banks 'should not be liquidated now'. \b0\par\par\uc2 544 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 October 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Forcing problematic banks to liquidate in the midst of the ongoing monetary crisis would further deteriorate confidence in the country's monetary sector and could spark a run on banks, the Econit Advisory Group says. \par \par \uc2  Econit's director Laksamana Sukardi said yesterday the government should not act hastily in forcing problem banks to liquidate and consolidate because such a measure could create new panic among customers and further damage the banking industry. \par \par \uc2  "It's likely bank liquidation would be done discriminately with banks owned by politically well-connected businesspeople escaping the axe," Laksamana said. \par \par \uc2  Such bias would cause \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  among people, and might worsen the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's confidence in the banking industry. This would in turn start a massive bank run where customers would move their funds to foreign banks, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The confidence crisis will soon spread to other banks which are perfectly healthy," he said. \par \par \uc2  Laksamana said the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which was negotiating with the government on a bailout package to solve the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil, might demand the liquidation of unsound banks as part of a deal. \par \par \uc2  But the IMF probably knew very little about the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the potential political impact of certain measures if taken, he said. \par \par \uc2  "This is not the United States, where policies are implemented equally. The risk of partiality on the part of the government is big," he said. \par \par \uc2  Citing Thailand as an example, he said the country's banking sector, which had suffered liquidity problems, had to be suspended because of massive bank runs. \par \par \uc2  The independent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  think tank predicts that 1998 will be "a year of correction", because there will be a correction in macro and microeconomic sectors from accumulated \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  errors. \par \par \uc2  "The party is over - now it's time to wash the dishes and pay the bill," Laksamana said. \par \par \uc2  Econit's director Rizal Ramli said Indonesia must pay the price of the currency turmoil with lower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and purchasing power and a wider socioeconomic gap. \par \par \uc2  The super-tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would affect the money supply next year and would impede investment growth, Rizal said. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia would enter a "stagflation" phase where \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would be slower and inflation would be high, he said. \par \par \uc2  The slow rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year would be followed by lower market demand and a higher unemployment rate. \par \par \uc2  Rizal said the government must give \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , full autonomy as in other countries to enable it to follow the dynamic activities of the money market. \par \par \uc2  The monetary council, consisting of the coordinating minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and finance, the finance minister, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  governor and the minister/state secretary, only slowed down the decision-making process to cope with the financial crisis, he said. \par \par \uc2  He said people should not expect the International Monetary Fund to eliminate graft practices in the country, such as corruption, which had been widely blamed as one of the factors that caused a loss of confidence in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The IMF could not make corruption and collusion disappear, Rizal said, adding that it would only be "wishful thinking". \par \par \uc2  "Everywhere in the world, collusion and corruption are eradicated through domestic reform," he said. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtas001na\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
