\par\par \b \uc2  Indonesia and IMF agree on reform package. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,310 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The following is the full text of the government press release on the reform package agreed upon by the Indonesian government and IMF after two weeks of negotiations: \par \par \uc2  The impact of an ongoing monetary crisis since July 1997 has been reflected in the drastic depreciation of the Southeast Asian currencies. This excessive depreciation could lead to an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises if not handled in a firm an timely manner. The currency turmoil has spread throughout East Asia, and last week we witnessed a drastic drop in stock market indexes in the United States, Europe, Latin America, East Asia and Australia. This is an indication that the volatility in financial markets and in capital markets has become a global phenomenon. \par \par \uc2  To minimize the negative impact of this volatility and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Indonesian government has taken a number of steps aimed at improving national efficiency, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  endurance and global competitiveness. Those steps include: \par \par \uc2  1. Adjustment of government expenditures so that the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  can, at a minimum, be maintained in a position of balance. \par \par \uc2  2. Adjustment of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and liquidity so as to stabilize the exchange rate. This is deemed necessary considering that the rupiah exchange rate has been floated and that monetary crises have been experienced throughout South East Asia. \par \par \uc2  3. Postponement and Review of government projects, state-owned enterprise projects, and private projects related to the government/state-owned enterprises, which was intended primarily to reduce the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the balance of payments. \par \par \uc2  4. Various efforts to boost exports and to provide incentives to exporters to sell their foreign currency. \par \par \uc2  5. A gradual reduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a loosening of liquidity designed to stimulate the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including small and medium scale business and cooperatives. \par \par \uc2  The above steps were implemented as a result of the limited cabinet meeting on Sept. 3, 1997, the government statement to the plenary session of the Indonesian parliament on Sept. 16, 1997, and the decision of the cabinet meeting on Oct. 8, 1997. These steps were taken to increase the confidence of the international community in Indonesia. The government is optimist that market confidence can be restored in light of the fact that the fundamentals of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are in general sound. \par \par \uc2  Although various programs and adjustment measures have been introduced by the government, nevertheless, as a member of certain international agencies including the International Monetary Funds (IMF), the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank (ADB), Indonesia frequently consults with these agencies. \par \par \uc2  Considering the international experience of the IMF, the World Bank and the ADB, and given that Indonesia is in need of technical assistance, the government has invited these agencies to review the various programs that have been, and will be, implemented by the government, so as to improve upon these programs. The IMF team, the World Bank and the ADB have been engaged in this review process since Oct. 17, 1997. \par \par \uc2  Programs have been formulated to cover actions in several areas, including: \par \par \uc2  a. efforts to restore the health of the financial sector \par \par \uc2  b. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  c. Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  including exchange rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2  d. Structural adjustment, in the form of an extension and deepening of the deregulation program \par \par \uc2  Considering the very broad scope of the program and the fact that it covers a number of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aspects, the program can only be implemented over a three-year period. In its implementation, it will b monitored tightly and will involve necessary reviews, and for that reason Indonesia will be assisted by experts from the IMF, the World Bank and the ADB. \par \par \uc2  Financial \par \par \uc2  The restoration of the health of the financial sector includes: \par \par \uc2  a. Banks, including private banks, government banks, and regional \par \par \uc2  development banks \par \par \uc2  b. Financial institutions \par \par \uc2  c. Insurance and pension funds \par \par \uc2  d. Capital market institutions such as mutual funds and securities houses \par \par \uc2  The program in the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector is basically aimed at increasing government revenue and reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and will be followed by an improvement of \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline so that during the 1997/1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year we will, at a minimum, succeed in avoiding a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year and the years thereafter, we are targeting a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  surplus of 1 percent Gross Domestic Products (GDP). The increase in government revenue will be achieved through strict discipline in non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  government revenue, in compliance with the law already ratified by the parliament. Moreover, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be aimed at reducing the current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the balance of payments so that within two years it can be reduced to less than 3 percent of GDP. \par \par \uc2  As a result of diminished \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth during the 1997/1998 and 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  years will decline, but the growth rate is predicted to rise again to approximately 7 percent by the year 1999/2000 and the years thereafter. \par \par \uc2  The program in the monetary sector will basically continue policies already enacted by enhancing our level of caution so that the inflation rate can be maintained at a single digit. Inflation will be restrained by controlling liquidity and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in order to both stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, on the one hand, and stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , on the other. \par \par \uc2  Objectives \par \par \uc2  The fundamental objective of the structural adjustment program is to increase national efficiency and the competitiveness of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To accomplish this objective, the steps to be implemented, among others, include: a. Gradual reduction of import tariffs, including those on chemical products, iron and steel, and fishery products, to 5 to 10 percent by the year 2003. Starting on Jan. 1, 1998, import tariffs on a large number of chemical products will be reduced by 5 percent, while tariffs on fishery products will be reduced from 10-20 percent to 5 percent. Most tariffs on iron and steel will also be reduced starting Jan. 1, 1999. b. Trade deregulation for various commodities, such as wheat and wheat flour, soybeans, and garlic. Starting on Jan. 1, 1998, these commodities can be imported freely under general importer status. Imports of soybeans and garlic will be subject to a 20 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  and imports of wheat flour will be subject to a 10 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to be reduced to 5 to 10 percent by the year 2003. To protect consumers, the government will temporarily provide a \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for wheat flour. Moreover, the administrative retail price of cement will be eliminated in the near future. c. Reduction of obstacles hindering exports, including export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to be implemented in stages. d. In line with government commitments to the World Trade Organization (WTO), the local content program for automobiles, which provides special tariffs for automobile producers who achieve high local content, will be eliminated by the year 2000. With reference to the national car project, the government has agreed to implement the decision of the WTO. e. In order to improve the efficiency of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government will review investment and \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, including government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  for state-owned enterprises and strategic industries. Meanwhile, the privatization will be continued, and will include the state-owned banks once merger of these banks is finalized. \par \par \uc2  All of these programs will be presented by the managing director of the IMF to the executive board, since they relate to the financial assistance from the IMF. \par \par \uc2  To support the implementation of the program, the aforementioned international agencies, together with a number of countries, have stated their intention to provide financial assistance, the amount and term of which have yet to be determined. The amount of financial assistance will be announced by each individual international agency and by each individual country. \par \par \uc2  The government firmly believes that these policies and programs will be effective in restoring the health of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  so as to improve the welfare of the people and alleviate poverty. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtb1001vb\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI-40 dropped 8.46% in October. \b0\par\par\uc2 483 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 November 1997\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Trade in shares on the Jakarta Stock Exchange(JSX) was unstimulated for the month of October. The volatile regional monetary situation cast its shadow over investors in the exchange. \par \par \uc2  The capitalists were haunted by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , mainly due to the continuous weakening in the Indonesian rupiah against the US dollar. These conditions made investors unwilling to take position on the stock market, and they tended to take a wait and see attitude regarding the IMF conclusion. \par \par \uc2  The hesitation on the part of investors in the JSX was mainly evidenced in the fluctuating movement of the Composite Price Index. The Composite Index rallied repeatedly, but would then show a sharp tendency to weaken again. For the month of October, the Comp took a sharp cut, by 8.46%, from 546.69(9/30) down to 500.42 on October 31, 1997. A similar drop occurred in the BI-40 Index, which weakened 6.01%, from 121.447 to 114.153. \par \par \uc2  The main factor in the fall in the Jakarta exchange was varied but \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  reports regarding the IMF aid. It was reported that the Indonesian government had requested the assistance of the IMF in the solution of the current Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  The request for help to the IMF was a controversial move among \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observers here. Those in favor of the move said that Indonesia must accept the IMF aid in order to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Those opposed to the move felt it was a mistake, since they believe the Monetary Authority, or Bank of Indonesia, should be able to overcome its difficulties alone. They do not want the IMF to dictate to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  However, all these opinions had no effect on the IMF, which is clear in light of the IMF/government negotiations, which continue to go on secretly. The talks have not yielded one clear and transparent conclusion, despite the fact that investors and the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  are waiting for news of the talks. \par \par \uc2  The conclusion of the IMF talks will have a serious effect on investors in the JSX. Foreign investors are hoping for openness on the part of the government in the form of an explanation of the IMF aid to be received, both technical and financial. One thing is certain, whatever the results of the talks, they must be announced, transparently, to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Particularly at this time, when the investors' confidence in the rupiah has been shaken by its continuing depreciation. The government is hoped to be able to restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence, with new, proactive measures, including the restoration of liquidity through the Bank of Indonesia Certificates(SBI), the reopening of SBPU(Money Market Securities), and no less important, transparency regarding the aid from the IMF. \par \par \uc2  This last is still being awaited by the investors, since the IMF decision will be a determining force on the exchange. (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010929dtb30004t\