\par\par \b \uc2  New government  \highlight22\uc2 economic policy \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 2,189 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The following is the full text of the government's statement on its new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  announced on Nov. 3, 1997. \par \par \uc2  1. The government is today announcing a series of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures. These measures are a continuation of policies formulated previously in the State Address delivered by the President of the Republic of Indonesia to the Parliament on August 16, 1997, in the Presidential Decision during the Limited cabinet Meeting for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Finance, Development Supervision, Production and Distribution on September 3, 1997 and October 8, 1997, and in the Government Statement of October 31, 1997. \par \par \uc2  2. In the State Address, the President stated: "we live in a world that is changing fast, a world that seems to be moving toward a great \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  union. Very often, events in one country or region immediately influence other countries or regions. The World Community is entering a new era: an era characterized by an open world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and trade." \par \par \uc2  3. In addition, the State Address set forth the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction to be implemented by the Government in anticipation of new challenges and opportunities emerging as a result of the rapid changes taking place throughout the world. To maximize the potential benefit and minimize the potential negative impact of these changes on our national development, the Government has introduced a number of deregulation and debureaucratization policies. \par \par \uc2  4. As we are all aware, the monetary crisis that began in July 1997 has led to a drastic depreciation of the Southeast Asian currencies. This excessive depreciation could result in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises if not handled in a firm and timely manner. \par \par \uc2  5. As mentioned in the Government Statement of October 31, 1997, in order to minimize the impact of the volatility and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has accompanied the monetary crises, the Indonesian Government has taken a number of steps aimed at improving national efficiency, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  endurance, and global competitiveness. Further implementation of these steps will be carried out through a number of programs in the following area: \par \par \uc2  5.1. Financial sector reforms; \par \par \uc2  5.2. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; \par \par \uc2  5.3. Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  including exchange rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; \par \par \uc2  5.4. Structural adjustment, in the form of an extension and deepening of the deregulation program. \par \par \uc2  The structural adjustment in each field is described in greater detail below: \par \par \uc2  A. Elimination of regulated imports \par \par \uc2  1. Import deregulation of wheat and wheat flour, soybeans and garlic \par \par \uc2  a. To accelerate the movement of imported goods either in the form of raw materials and intermediary goods used to further increase the efficiency of our industry, or in the form of consumption goods, various import regulations and import procedures will be simplified. \par \par \uc2  b. This includes elimination of import regulations for soybeans, garlic and wheat flour, which previously could be imported only by BULOG. These products can now be imported by General Importers (IU), subject to import tariffs that will come into effect on January 1, 1998. The \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  changes for these products will be as follows: \par \par \uc2  1) Dried garlic: the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be raised from 0% to 20%; \par \par \uc2  2) Dried soybeans: the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be raised from 0% to 20%; \par \par \uc2  3) Wheat flour: the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be raised from 0% to 10%; \par \par \uc2  By the year 2003, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  on these three products will be reduced to 5%. \par \par \uc2  c. During the next 3-5 years, distribution system of wheat flour will be as follows: \par \par \uc2  (1) Wheat Flour mills will appoint BULOG as the domestic flour distributor \par \par \uc2  (2) BULOG will distribute this wheat flour to the food industry, to small industries, to groceries, to outlets, and to other consumers; \par \par \uc2  (3) In the end consumers will receive Government \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at an amount equal to the difference between factory selling price and consumers buying price. \par \par \uc2  d. BULOG is given the responsibility to stabilize the supply and price of rice and sugar. \par \par \uc2  2. Elimination of the Administration Retail Price (HPS) for cement. \par \par \uc2  a. With the rising output of cement factories leading to a supply of cement in excess of domestic needs, market mechanisms can now be relied upon to safeguard the interests of consumers in an efficient manner. \par \par \uc2  b. With the improved functioning of market mechanism in the supply and demand for cement, the Administrative Retail Price (HPS) for cement is no longer needed. Therefore, the HPS for cement is eliminated with the Decree of the Minister of Industry and Trade No.403/MPP/Kep/97. \par \par \uc2  c. With the elimination of the HPS for cement, the interest of investors in developing cement factories can be raised in line with demand and the opening-up of market opportunities. \par \par \uc2  B. Export facilitation \par \par \uc2  1. Expansion of the groups and types of products eligible for coverage under the Special Export Firm (PET) facility. \par \par \uc2  a. In order to increase non-oil/gas exports, the range of products covered under the PET facility is extended and enlarged to a total of 18 product groups. This is regulated through the Decree of the Minister of Industry. \par \par \uc2  b. Previously, the PET facility was limited to 10 commodity groups, namely: textiles and textile products, finished leather/footwear/leather products, electronics, wood and processed rattan, pulp/paper/paper products, process food, vegetable oil, processed natural rubber, dolls and toys, and frozen fish shrimp. \par \par \uc2  c. With the above decree, coverage is broadened to include 8 additional commodity groups, namely: iron and steel, automotive components, machinery and machinery components, jewelry, chemicals, rubber, mineral products and plastic sheets. \par \par \uc2  d. In additional, when exporting under PET facilities, non-producer exporting companies with PET status are no longer limited to longer limited to the export of those products included in the PET coverage list. However, this provision does not apply if the export of the product is prohibited. \par \par \uc2  2. Standard conversion factors for utilization of raw materials and intermediary goods. \par \par \uc2  a. Efforts to increase production efficiency and export activities for products such as textiles, sport shoes, leather shoes and tanned shoes, will be facilitated by implementing Standard Conversion Factors for raw materials and intermediary goods. \par \par \uc2  b. This is regulated through the Decree of the Minister of Industry and Trade No. 404/MPP/Kep/11/97. \par \par \uc2  3. Import tariffs and export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  In order to improve business conditions, efficiency and national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  endurance, while increasing the competitiveness of domestic products in the international market, the Minister of Finance issues the following decrees: \par \par \uc2  a. The Decree of the Minister of Finance No 542/KMK.01/1997 regarding a schedule for reducing import tariffs on certain fish products, chemical products and metal products, which stipulates that: \par \par \uc2  1) The import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  for certain fresh, cold or frozen fish (salmon, trout, skip jack, etc.), currently subject to 10% and 20% tariffs, is scheduled to be reduced to 5% in 1998 and 0% in 2003; \par \par \uc2  2) Tariffs on certain chemical products (ethylene, propylene, styrene, polyethylene, polypropylene, polystyrene) currently subject to tariffs of 25% 30% and 40%, are scheduled to be reduced to 20% in the year 2000 and 10% in 2003. In 1998, tariffs on styrene and polystyrene will be reduced from 30% to 25%, while tariffs on polypropylene and polyethylene will be reduced from 40% to 35%; \par \par \uc2  3) Tariffs on certain metal products are scheduled to be reduced, including: \par \par \uc2  a) Coated Steel, from the current \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate of 15% to 10% in 2003; \par \par \uc2  b) Other steel products (billet and profile): \par \par \uc2  (1) Products with tariffs currently at 30% will experience no change in their \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1998. Tariffs on these products are scheduled to be reduced to 20% in 2000 and to 10% in 2003. \par \par \uc2  (2) Tariffs on products currently subject to a 25% in 1998, and are scheduled to be reduced to 15% to 20% in 2000, and to 10% in 2003. \par \par \uc2  b. With the elimination of regulated imports for certain products, the decree of the Minister of Finance concerning the Adjustment and Scheduling of import tariffs on certain products is stipulated as follows: \par \par \uc2  1) In 1998 the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  on dried garlic is raised from 0% to 20%. The import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  of dried garlic will be lowered to 15% in the year 2000 and to 5% in 2003. \par \par \uc2  2) In 1998 the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  on soybeans is raised from 0% to 20%. The import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  of dried garlic will remain at 20% in the year 2000 and will be lowered to 5% in 2003. \par \par \uc2  3) In 1998 the import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  on wheat flour is raised from 0% to 10%. It will be lowered to 5% in 2003. \par \par \uc2  c. In addition, in order to spur export growth and to increase foreign exchange earnings, export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on certain commodities with high export potential are scheduled to be reduced, namely: rattan, raw hide leather, iron ores, tin ores, copper ores, silver ores and various other mineral ores, processed and raw natural cork, and aluminum scrap. \par \par \uc2  4. Elimination of income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on gold bars \par \par \uc2  To increase non-oil/gas exports, and in particular exports of gold jewelry, the article 22 income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (withholding \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) on imported gold bars used to produce gold jewelry for export is eliminated. \par \par \uc2  5. Elimination of Value Added \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PPN) for Indirect Exports. \par \par \uc2  To facilitate exports from companies with Special Export Firm (PET) status, the provision of raw materials and services by domestic suppliers to firms with PET status will not be subject to value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PPN). Rebates of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fees to these suppliers will be expedited. \par \par \uc2  6. Loosening the sale of components produced by companies in bonded zones (PDKB) and other Indonesian customs areas (DPIL). \par \par \uc2  To Improve the investment climate and to increase the growth of domestic industries, companies located in Bonded Zones will be allowed to sell their products on the domestic market, in the form of components, but with domestic sales not exceeding 50% of realized export values. \par \par \uc2  B. Simplification of import permits and procedures. \par \par \uc2  1. Quarantine of leather used as raw material Presidential decree No. 46/1997 stipulates: \par \par \uc2  a. raw leather and wet pickle leather may be imported only from countries free of major contagious animal diseases. \par \par \uc2  b. Only preserved raw leather will be subject to quarantine. Wet Pickle leather from countries free of major contagious animal diseases, wet blue leather, crust leather and finished leather, will not be subject to quarantine. \par \par \uc2  c. Import approval from the Director General f Livestock is only needed for the import of preserved raw leather. \par \par \uc2  2. Bonded zone import procedures. \par \par \uc2  a. Permission to establish Bonded Zones, which play a very important role in raising exports, will no longer be issued by the President, but instead will be granted by the Minister of Finance as stipulated in the Presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PP) No. 43/1997 \par \par \uc2  b. Investors with business activities in Bonded Zones are permitted to engage in storage and warehousing activities in the Bonded Zones. \par \par \uc2  C. Business climate \par \par \uc2  1. Improvement of decrees regulating Distributors and Retail Outlets \par \par \uc2  a. In line with the growing openness and integration of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the role of licensed foreign investment companies (PMA) in increasing their dual roles in national business should be encouraged. \par \par \uc2  b. For this reason, the Government (through Government Stipulation No. 41 and 42/1997) stipulates and improvement of the decrees for distributors and retail outlets, as follows: \par \par \uc2  1) Foreign investment companies (PMA) engaged in production will be permitted to be distributors or wholesalers for their own products throughout Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  2) Foreign investment companies (PMA) engaged in production can appoint other foreign investment companies established for this purpose as their distributor or wholesaler throughout Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  3) Foreign investment companies (PMA) engaged in production can appoint any Indonesian Company which has no foreign investment participation as their distributor or wholesaler and/or retailer throughout Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  4) Starting on January 1, 2003, foreign investment can sell their products throughout Indonesia directly to final consumers through foreign companies specially established for this purpose. \par \par \uc2  4. This \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to have a positive impact and to produce benefits by: \par \par \uc2  1). Attracting foreign investors to invest their capital in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  2). Encouraging the transfer of technology and management skills to the distribution system. \par \par \uc2  3). Expanding trade business activities. \par \par \uc2  2. Foreign representatives \par \par \uc2  a. To raise the awareness of foreign consumers concerning the potential of Indonesia's regional products, foreign trade representatives will be allowed to open Foreign Trade Representatives offices in each provincial capital city, as set forth in the Decree of the Minister of Trade and Industry No. 402/MPP/Kep/11/97. \par \par \uc2  b. It is expected that this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  will have a beneficial impact by: \par \par \uc2  1. Providing a greater opportunity for parties outside the country to become further acquainted with the characteristics of national products available for export, so as to raise non-oil gas exports. \par \par \uc2  2. Broadening employment opportunities for Indonesians. \par \par \uc2  3. Increasing the use of Indonesian companies in conducting market surveys needed by these trade representatives. \par \par \uc2  4. Import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities for machinery and raw materials for developing and expanding industry and services. \par \par \uc2  To support the expansion and development of industry, it is reaffirmed that industry is granted import facilities allowing two years of duty-free imports of machinery, equipment, and supporting goods and materials. Similarly, service industries are granted import facilities allowing two years of duty-free imports of machinery and equipment. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtb4001y7\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  MARKET REPORT - IMF reforms carry BI-40. \b0\par\par\uc2 612 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 1997\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  After announcing the US$ 23 billion in IMF aid, the liquidation of 16 banks and a reforms program, the IMF-Indonesia negotiations conclusion has not fully restored the confidence of investors in the market. \par \par \uc2  Although in the first session of trade the index increased 10 points in anticipation by investors of a report on the IMF aid, investors still felt some concern over possible renewed speculation in foreign currency, in light of the fact that the rupiah has jumped to far too fast against the dollar, by about 320 points, closing yesterday at Rp 3,290 per US dollar. In order to avoid the risk of such speculation, investors preferred short selling. \par \par \uc2  Investors could be seen still in shock following the closure of 16 banks, which was announced by BI last Saturday. At the same time, foreign investors could be seen holding back from entering the stock exchange, as they observed market developments. The resulting market sentiment was not enough to bring a significant increase to the index. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange(JSX) Composite Price Index gained slightly, by 0.26%(1.296), to 501.714. Not unrelated, Bisnis Indonesia's index of the top 40 choice stocks on the Jakarta exchange, the BI-40 Index, increased by 0.395 points,(0.35%), from 114.153, to 114.548. \par \par \uc2  Elsewhere, the agreement by the international community to settle the monetary crisis in Southeast and East Asia brought positive growth to the Asia-Pacific exchanges. In yesterday's trade, the Hang Seng Index at Hong Kong increased 5.94% to 11,255.11, followed in Singapore by the Straits Times Index, up 7.43%, and in Kuala Lumpur, where the KLSE Comp closed up by 7.83%, the Manila Comp gaining 0.39%, the Seoul exchange jumping 8.68%, the Taiwan index up by 4.55% and the SET Index at Thailand up 0.05%. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 0.82% in last Friday's trade to 7,442.08. \par \par \uc2  Investors confidence in the stability of the rupiah against the US dollar was strengthening. However, investors were still waiting to hear about the real sector deregulation policies, in the form of lowered tariffs, which are to be initiated on January 1, 1998. At the same time, the eradication of a cement \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  resulted in a positive response toward cement industry stocks by investors. \par \par \uc2  Some stocks on the BI-40 showed sharp increases in yesterday's trade, including HM Sampoerna, up 10 points, to Rp 6,525, followed by Semen Gresik, up nine points to Rp 3,725, Telkom up five points to Rp 3,475 and Hero Supermarket, up three points. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, a rumor that banks slated to be liquidated will have their assets taken over by Bank Niaga, BII, Bank Lippo and Bank Bali increased investors interest in those banks. It was no surprise that Bank Lippo stock increased by three points, to Rp 1,075. \par \par \uc2  The transfer of stock portfolios by investors at this time is not only focused on stocks benefiting from the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms coming from the agreement between the IMF and the Indonesian government, but us also directed at listed companies with corporate action. \par \par \uc2  In general, the stocks this week are predicted to improve significantly, assuming that the market players do not collect their profits too quickly. Particularly since world-class speculator, George Soros, has said the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  turn of events in Southeast and East Asia will be ending. If this is true, then the foreign investors should be coming back to the exchange and the trade on the stock market will improve drastically. (*). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010929dtb400050\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Bank Panin increases its cash  \highlight22\uc2 reserves \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 409 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 1997\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Bank Panin has increased its cash \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to 50% above its normal level, in anticipation of the possibility of increased withdrawals following the government decision to revoke the business licenses of 16 banks. \par \par \uc2  Deputy Managing Director at Bank Panin, Roosniati Salihin said the move to close the 16 banks would not have mush effect on the operation of the bank. "The withdrawal of cash will be very low, less than Rp 1 million," he said to Bisnis yesterday. \par \par \uc2  She acknowledged that the liquidations would bring some effect, great or small to the other, sound banks. However, she explained, the banks are prepared to face the possibility of a panic among the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which might cause them to withdraw their funds from the banks. "We have increased our cash \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  from 2% to 3%." \par \par \uc2  In the confusion of being a bank customer, there is a chance some customers will be seen withdrawing their rupiah to buy US dollars. "They are still confused." \par \par \uc2  Managing Director of Bank Panin, Rostian Sjamsudin added that amid the still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  monetary conditions, the performance of Bank Panin has improved. By the end of September, he explained, the working capital at Bank Panin increased to Rp 1 trillion, from an end of 1996 level of Rp 850 billion, following a rights issue by the bank. \par \par \uc2  In the last nine months, he said, the bank has earned a net profit of Rp 83 billion less 3% needed to protect outstnding loans, a 37% improvement. The operational earnings were Rp 764 billion, a 33% increase, and interest earnings were Rp 695 billion, a 34% increase. \par \par \uc2  By the end of September 1997, the total assets of Bank Panin increased to Rp 6.8 trillion, a 41% increase over the end of last year. \par \par \uc2  There was also an increase in credits, to Rp 3.7 trillion, while third party funds were Rp 3.2 trillion. The total Bank Panin assets were Rp 6.3 trillion. \par \par \uc2  With this financial performance, according to Rostian, the capital adequacy ratio(CAR) of Bank Panin is at around 19.5%, far above the BI requirement of 9%. The return on assets(ROA) is 1.82%, and the ratio of funds to credit(LDR) is 76%. \par \par \uc2  Amid the recent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, he explained, the management must continuously make an effort to assist the small/middle-sized businesses and cooperatives, so they can survive the turmoil. (ep). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010929dtb400052\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  " \highlight22\uc2 Public \highlight\uc2  banks await liquidation certainty". \b0\par\par\uc2 395 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 1997\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Association of Issuers (AEI) asked that the government be more transparent in providing criteria of the banks that have been liquidated so as to give certainty to banks that have gone \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Banks that have gone \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  are nervous. They ask what are the government's criteria in taking the decision to liquidate," said Rosano Barack, Chairman of AEI, in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  According to Rosano, various banks already on the stock exchange are worried because the unclear criteria given by the government in liquidating the bank. "They feel that the rumours circulating are discomforting." \par \par \uc2  The unclear emitters from the bank, he continued, among other things was caused by events that struck Bank Andromeda although the bank's owners have tried to fulfil their obligations; despite that, the bank has been liquidated. \par \par \uc2  Rosano said that this matter noted the liquidation of 16 banks made by the government last week. He was thankful that of all those banks, not one originated from a bank that had gone \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  According to Rosano, the government now must be more open by announcing problems of al the banks that were liquidated so that other bankers (including those who have gone \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) will not be chased by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "I think the government should be open about which banks are 'ailing' and 'culpable' as well as when the problems of the bank arose. If the criteria is not clear, there will be problems." \par \par \uc2  Although that is the case, he said, AEI welcomed the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to liquidate the banks considered troubled because that action should be taken in the broader interests. \par \par \uc2  "There is resolve from the government that banking must be good because it is the backbone of the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," said Rosano. \par \par \uc2  He also suggested that banks that have fulfilled the conditions to be listed on the stock exchange quickly make a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offering because going \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  has proved to have many advantages for banking. \par \par \uc2  "A proven bank that has gone \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  has stronger durability in facing a crisis. Besides being more transparent, they also have it relatively more easy in gathering funds," he said. \par \par \uc2  Because of that, said Rosano, who is also vice president of PT Bimantara Citra, small private banks as well as the biggest are better off making a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offering as quickly as possible. (amu). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010929dtb400056\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
