\par\par \b \uc2  MARKET REPORT - Stocks plunged on regional bearish market. \b0\par\par\uc2 457 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Share prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) plunged for a third consecutive day yesterday on the impact of regional weakness and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the local market. \par \par \uc2  The JSX composite price index, the main price indicator, fell 12.79 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 466.11, with 473.4 million shares changing hands at Rp 518.4 billion (US$159.50 million). \par \par \uc2  Brokers said trading activities were volatile as foreign and domestic investors dumped blue chip shares on fears that the legal suit by President Soeharto's son Bambang Trihatmodjo against the closure of his bank would harm the government's credibility. \par \par \uc2  But most analysts believed the bearish condition would continue due to gloomier prospects of the country's corporate earnings. \par \par \uc2  "I think foreign investors stayed out of the market in fear of deteriorating corporate earnings this year due to the currency crisis," the head of research at Socgen Crosby Indonesia, Goei Siauw Hong, told The Jakarta Post yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said the IMF bailout package for Indonesia would not immediately help restore Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the short term as the main purpose of the IMF-led package was to improve the country's long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Goei predicted that Indonesian companies with dollar denominated debts would find it more difficult in the coming months. \par \par \uc2  "Major overseas creditors will force Indonesian companies to change their long-term liabilities to short-term ones," he said. \par \par \uc2  "The change of these liabilities will create a cash-flow problem for most companies in Indonesia," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said the currency crisis would cause an increase in unemployment as most companies would have to let some of their employees go due to a lack of liquidity. \par \par \uc2  "This problem, coupled with the possibility of an intense riot before the General Assembly in March to elect a new president, will certainly force foreign investors to track sideways," he said. \par \par \uc2  He predicted that the market would continue to see bearish market conditions until the third quarter next year. \par \par \uc2  "I think the index will continue to decline in the coming months and will see a downtrend market sentiment in the first six months of next year," he said. \par \par \uc2  A stock dealer said the legal dispute between businesspeople and the government over bank closures partly contributed to sluggish trading yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Bambang Trihatmodjo, who has a 25 percent stake in liquidated Bank Andromeda, filed a suit against Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor J. Soedradjad Djiwandono Wednesday. The President's half-brother Probosutedjo, whose Bank Jakarta was one of 16 ailing banks closed by the government, also launched a similar legal battle against the government. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtb80023a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Government asked to disclose the amount of private debt. \b0\par\par\uc2 802 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 November 1997\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government, said an observer, should immediately announce the private foreign debt that is now due. \par \par \uc2  According to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer, Sri Edi Swasono, the government must be consistent in its attention to the two sectors which have rocked the Indonesian monetary condition, that is, the private foreign debt now due and the activities of mischievous speculators. \par \par \uc2  "That is why the government must immediately identify and announce the private debt now due," said Sri Edi at a seminar entitled "The National \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the Direction of Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Development for the Next Five Years" here at the end of last week. \par \par \uc2  The government, he says, must show its face, and announce the private foreign debtors, as well as those responsible for the 16 banks to be liquidated, in order to provide a sense of fairness. "The names of the speculators should also be announced by the government, for the sake of fairness, and to deter the speculators." \par \par \uc2  The government, represented by the Minister of Finance, is scheduled to provide a clarification to the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  Assembly regarding the IMF aid package and the decision to liquidate the 16 banks at a plenary session to be held today. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, DPR member, Thomas Suyatno, predicts that if the private debt is not rescheduled, then the private position will continue to worsen in the eyes of the international community. \par \par \uc2  According to Suyatno, who is also head of the Perbanas, the Association of Domestic Private Banks Guidance Council, private debt as of February 1998 will be US$ 15 billion. \par \par \uc2  "If the this private debt cannot be renewed, the position of the domestic private sector will go down, which will in turn increase the country risk, and decrease trust in Indonesia," he said at the end of last week. \par \par \uc2  He said that the Bank of Indonesia(BI) Governor once said the current private debt coming from securities and commercial papers is US$ 60 billion. \par \par \uc2  "Of this amount, it is calculated that 25 large scale companies have debt coming due in the next six months. This will be no small amount, at about US$ 15 billion," said Thomas Suyatno. \par \par \uc2  As a result of the continuing monetary crisis, he said, the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  harmony and self confidence, which has been solid for years, has been shaken. \par \par \uc2  "The majority of the business community is experiencing an extraordinary panic," he said. \par \par \uc2  He predicts that if this crisis goes on beyond the end of 1997, hundreds, and even thousands, of large, middle and small scale businesses will default on their debt for a lack of adequate liquidity. \par \par \uc2  In a monetary crisis accompanied by a high level of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  players, particularly the big ones, will not only act to save themselves, but will join in speculation in order to turn a profit from the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  concerning when the crisis will end. \par \par \uc2  Debt management \par \par \uc2  Regarding private debt, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer Mari E. Pangestu, of CSIS(Centre for Strategic and International Studies) says that following the currency crisis, which was marked by the huge amount of private debt, the question arose as to whether private debt should be controlled by the government. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia adheres to the free foreign exchange system, which means the government must not interfere with debt between private parties. But there should be government controls," said Mari yesterday. \par \par \uc2  She said that there is an urgent need for a foreign debt management system. Mari suggests that the private sector report how it uses this debt to the government. \par \par \uc2  Even that, she says, will not guarantee adequate control. "The Malaysian and Singaporean governments have a very accurate reporting system, but they too ended up over exposed." \par \par \uc2  B