\par\par \b \uc2  Selecting the right bank amid clamor from rumor mill. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Laksamana Sukardi \par \uc2 667 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Selecting the right bank is even tougher these days. \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertain economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  times have affected people's ability to think logically and left them easily swayed by groundless rumors. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , confused and dismayed after the recent closure of 16 insolvent banks, needs responsible explanations from the monetary and banking authorities on the healthiness of banks still operating. \par \par \uc2   <Op In a recent survey, The Economist magazine attributed failure of banks in emerging market countries, including Indonesia, to four main reasons - a severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn, excessive lending to sister companies in the same business group, excessive intervention by governments and banking liberalization which is not followed up by prudential regulations. \par \par \uc2  As the nation is currently experiencing an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn, it is understandable that people are easily panicked and vulnerable to rumors. Those who cannot afford to travel abroad regularly do not have the option to transfer their money to banks in other countries. \par \par \uc2  That leaves no choice but to be more cautious in selecting domestic banks. Here are several tips for depositors to be circumspect in selecting the bank for their money. \par \par \uc2  Put in a nutshell, depositors need to evaluate the quantitative and qualitative aspects of a bank. \par \par \uc2  The quantitative aspect can be evaluated from the financial reports routinely released by the bank in print media. From the reports, depositors can ascertain the bank's financial ratios - its capital adequacy ratio (CAR), loan to deposit ratio (LDR) and profitability. \par \par \uc2  If the ratios meet requirements set by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the bank can be considered more or less healthy. \par \par \uc2  This quantitative aspect does have weaknesses. Financial reports, for example, are complicated and not practical for the layman's understanding. \par \par \uc2  Furthermore, publication of financial reports is always late, generally several months after the date of the data recorded, whereas the asset and liability conditions of a bank change dynamically. Drastic changes can occur in a minute. \par \par \uc2  People will be more comfortable in using the qualitative aspect. This is an important determinant, but its evaluation is not easy. \par \par \uc2  Most important factors of the qualitative aspect are the management of the bank and the conditions of its shareholders. \par \par \uc2  The management of the bank has a great role in the changes of its healthiness. If the directors manage the bank conservatively, it is generally healthier than a bank managed speculatively. \par \par \uc2  But in some cases, the management of a bank is heavily influenced by shareholders, because they are the ones recruiting the directors and determining their bonuses. Overly dominant shareholders will determine the style of management and, in turn, influence the healthiness of the bank. \par \par \uc2  During a period of financial \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , people feel more comfortable in depositing in banks whose shareholders are well-known, wealthy and have solid reputations. \par \par \uc2  Evaluating a bank based on the quality of the shareholders is also risky because even though they have fine reputations, they, as human beings, can change. When someone is fully entrusted to manage funds without any supervision, it will be easier for him to abuse that trust. \par \par \uc2  The best banks are those owned by affluent shareholders who have good reputations and integrity, but who cannot make arbitrary decisions on its operation because a good supervision system is in place. \par \par \uc2  How is the supervision implemented? If the bank has only one shareholder, it would inevitably be difficult to implement a good supervision system. The more shareholders the bank has, the better the supervision will be. \par \par \uc2  But if a bank is owned by too many shareholders, it might find it difficult to grow because it will be less sensitive to changes and slow in making decisions. \par \par \uc2  Good shareholding is a combination of institutional and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  shareholders. The combination will force the directors to operate the bank carefully and prepare transparent reports. \par \par \uc2  There is still reason for caution. The continuing likelihood of subjectivity makes it difficult for depositors to fully evaluate the reputation and credibility of individual shareholders. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtbn002v6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
