\par\par \b \uc2  Anxious  \highlight22\uc2 public \highlight\uc2  seeks truth on safest banks. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,015 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  A crisis of confidence is rattling many following the recent closure of 16 private banks and last week's massive rumor-sparked rush on Bank Central Asia (BCA), the country's largest private bank. Depositors' top priority today is not \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  or tempting incentives, but whether the bank will still be in business tomorrow. The Jakarta Post reporters Ida Indawati Khouw, IGGP Bayu Ismoyo, Johannes Simbolon, K. Basrie, Lukman Natanegara, Primastuti Handayani, Sugianto Tandra, Sylvia Gratia M.N. and Yogita Tahil Ramani tap the issue. Related stories on Page 9. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Flower trader Dadang pointed to gleaming, multistoried Bank Harapan Sentosa (BHS) on Jl. Gajah Mada, Central Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  "Did anyone think that a bank with such impressive headquarters and with so many branches could be closed down by the government?" \par \par \uc2  The 43-year-old had Rp 850,000 (US$246) deposited in BHS, one of the banks liquidated on Nov. 1. \par \par \uc2  "How could lower-class people like me know about the men behind the institution and the bank's financial problems?" \par \par \uc2  Dadang, like so many people dazed by the tumultuous events of the past few months, is now nervy about where to put his money. \par \par \uc2  In a bitter lesson in the importance of choosing substance over style when it comes to finances, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains over Rp 11.7 trillion of depositors' funds in the liquidated banks. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  anxiety culminated last week in the rush on BCA. Fueled by unfounded rumors of the death of bank founder Soedono Salim, customers withdrew billions of rupiah in a matter of hours. \par \par \uc2  Adding fuel to the fire of apprehension is the recent statement by Bambang Trihatmodjo, a shareholder in Andromeda Bank, one of the liquidated banks. \par \par \uc2  President Soeharto's second eldest son said 90 percent of all the banks here had violated the legal lending limit, one of the government's stipulations in the bank closures. \par \par \uc2  "I bet that there's not a single businessman here who knows where to put his money," said oil company executive Wimin Berlim. \par \par \uc2  "Many say that state or foreign banks are safer. But, still they say it with hesitation. It seems that we're facing a crisis of confidence." \par \par \uc2  Electing to save in banks overseas, he said, would only worsen the monetary woes. "Of course, we do not want to do that for the sake of our country's future, right?" \par \par \uc2  Banking analyst Laksamana Sukardi agrees that the powder keg of confusion and worry is exacerbating people's efforts to make the right banking choices. \par \par \uc2  "At present, people cannot think rationally. Instead, they are swayed by groundless rumors," said the former managing director of Lippo Bank. \par \par \uc2  There are reports of big transfers of accounts from private banks to state and foreign institutions. \par \par \uc2  Dadang Surachman, spokesman for Bank Negara Indonesia (BNI), acknowledged the state bank had acquired many new depositors following the recent liquidation. \par \par \uc2  Trend \par \par \uc2  Ekky Syachrudin, a member of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' Commission VIII for state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs, said: "The trend persisted for some time until state banks recently lowered their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  on savings, which means the banks are very liquid now." \par \par \uc2  Beleaguered private banks are battling a calamitous reversal of fortune. \par \par \uc2  During the past decade, and particularly since the Pakto 1988 banking \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , people scrambled to put their money in private banks, enticed by high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a range of attractive incentives. \par \par \uc2  The issuance of the October 1988 \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  - which permitted any party to set up a bank with minimum paid-up capital of Rp 10 billion - opened the floodgates for risk-taking entrepreneurs. \par \par \uc2  The number of private banks soared past 200. \par \par \uc2  Unfortunately, among their ranks were unscrupulous businesspeople. They recklessly used depositors' funds for intra-group lending to strengthen their business empires. \par \par \uc2  Six of 90 banks founded after the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  came into effect were among those liquidated. \par \par \uc2  Most of the rest, plus several older institutions, are believed to be in dire financial straits. \par \par \uc2  Mergers are considered their best options to remain afloat. \par \par \uc2  According to Kontan \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  newsweekly, the government will issue a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  dividing banks into three groups based on owners' paid-up capital: more than Rp 1 trillion, between Rp 1 trillion and Rp 300 billion, and less than Rp 300 billion. \par \par \uc2  Only seven state and five private banks fall into the first group from the current roster of 221 banks (see table on Page 9). \par \par \uc2  The grouping system would also curtail lending limits on the banks. \par \par \uc2  Questions remain on whether the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be enough to restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence. \par \par \uc2  For the time being, people may be best served by their own judgment. Analysts say the measure of healthy banks can be made through considering financial reports, shareholders and type of management. \par \par \uc2  This is still not a surefire method of detecting the good from the bad, especially with the seemingly wealthy backers of some banks believed to be in trouble. \par \par \uc2  In descending order of priority, people now prefer to save at banks with good reputations, in convenient locations and with attractive incentives. \par \par \uc2  Some are adopting additional safeguards, keeping different currency accounts at several banks. \par \par \uc2  "I now know that safety is better than high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," said Lisma, the owner of hundreds of rental houses in South Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  "So I believe that saving money at two or three banks, state and top private banks, is a wise step." \par \par \uc2  A security guard in West Jakarta advised: "Beware of banks which offer you high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and lots of hefty prizes and promises. They are definitely in financial trouble." \par \par \uc2  Legislator Ekky warns that building people's confidence is essential to the overall health of the banking sector. \par \par \uc2  "Without their confidence, the banking system will collapse in the end, since it is from the people the banks get their fund," he says. \par \par \uc2  It will take more than soothing words and promising \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators to assuage people like Dadang burned by the bank liquidation. \par \par \uc2  He may be able to recoup his funds, but he has also learned the hard way that respectable appearances really can be deceptive. (team) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtbn002w2\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
