\par\par \b \uc2  Investors get two-year extension to start projects. \b0\par\par\uc2 488 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 November 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government has decided to grant a two-year extension to local and foreign investors facing difficulty in starting their projects on time, State Minister for Investment Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo said yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto, also the chairman of the Investment Coordinating Board, told a hearing of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  that investors having difficulty should apply for the extension from the ministry. \par \par \uc2  Investors who are granted permits for projects are normally required to start their project within three years. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto said several companies had already applied for the extension. \par \par \uc2  "Until the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns to normal again, we are taking a lenient approach to investment firms that cannot meet their deadlines," he told members of House Commission V for manpower, trade and investment. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto said some investors and companies had had to delay the implementation of their commitments due to the currency crisis, which has seen around a 35 percent drop in the value of the rupiah since July. \par \par \uc2  Over 90 percent of the investors' funds did not come from their own equities but from bank loans, most of which were from offshore banks, he said. Dollar appreciation has inflated the loan values, he said. \par \par \uc2  The tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed by the government to defend the rupiah had also shot up the credit \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in local banks, thus lowering demand for loans to finance the projects, he said. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto said he expected the rate of investment this year and next year to decline because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. \par \par \uc2  He did not detail the likely decline, saying the ministry had no way of predicting it at this stage. \par \par \uc2  "Between 1992 and this year, an average of 47 percent of the investment commitments had been made by local investors, while 53 percent were made by foreign investors every year," he said. \par \par \uc2  "But the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , so that we would not expect the starting rate between last July and next March to be anything like that in the past four and a half years," he said. \par \par \uc2  The ministry expects an inflow of foreign and domestic investment of around Rp 224.7 trillion (US$61.41 billion) during the sixth five year development plan, which will end on March 31, 1999. \par \par \uc2  Sanyoto said investors' enthusiasm to make commitments had not declined, despite the monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  Between January and Nov. 8, local investors had committed to Rp 110 trillion in investments in the country, and foreign investors $29.6 billion, he said. \par \par \uc2  In the whole of last year, local investors committed about Rp 100.7 trillion and foreign investors $29.9 billion, he said. \par \par \uc2  Investment commitments increased by Rp 3.18 trillion in October from the previous month, to Rp 17.58 trillion for 149 projects. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors made up $4.88 billion of the commitment and local investors Rp 12.7 trillion, he said. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtbp002af\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
