\par\par \b \uc2  Ad firms told to cross creative front. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Budiman Moerdijat. \par \uc2 798 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 December 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Enhancing creativity and developing more professional personnel are the most formidable challenges lying ahead for the advertising industry, a noted executive believes. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Indonesian Association of Advertising Agencies, Yusca Ismail, said these elements were necessary to boost the quality of locally produced advertisements. \par \par \uc2  "There were a number of awards in the Citra Adhi Pariwara which could not be given to the nominees since they were below expectations," said the general manager of the Perwanal/DMB&B advertising agency. \par \par \uc2  He said the occurrence at this year's Citra Adhi Pariwara - an annual industry award for members of the advertising association agency - indicated the problems in stale creativity. \par \par \uc2  The sector has somewhat exhausted itself in terms of new ideas, he told The Jakarta Post in a recent interview. \par \par \uc2  "There is a lack of novel and fresh ideas in our advertisements...we need more advertisements which can 'excite' the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  He said the small number of local qualified advertising executives were overburdened. \par \par \uc2  "As a result, the few professional people cannot concentrate on the quality of their work." \par \par \uc2  Yusca said the shortage was understandable as advertising was a relatively new sector in the country. \par \par \uc2  "We are still in the early stages of the advertising industry, especially in TV commercials." \par \par \uc2  That is where expatriate advertising executives comes in, he said. \par \par \uc2  Local advertising executives should gain knowledge of marketing communication from their foreign counterparts, he added. \par \par \uc2  "We should learn both the concept and the implementation of the concept." \par \par \uc2  Yusca described another obstacle as the time needed for local advertising executives to learn skills from foreign workers. \par \par \uc2  Despite affiliations of foreign advertising agencies with local operations since the early 1970s, transfer of knowledge, particularly in know-how for TV commercials, was disrupted when the government banned commercials from state-owned TV network, TVRI, in 1982. \par \par \uc2  "We had to start all over again when the government allowed the operation of private TV stations in 1989," Yusca said. \par \par \uc2  Advertising, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations and business communications magazine, Cakram, reported in its latest edition that international advertising agencies, predominantly from the United States, continue to make their presence felt due to Indonesia's huge potential market. \par \par \uc2  These include Lintas (Ammirati Puris Lintas), J. Walter Thompson (JWT/AdForce), Ogilvy & Mather (IndoAd), DMB&B (Perwanal), BBDO, McCann-Erickson (Grafik), Leo Burnett (Kreasindo), FCB (FCB/Advis), DDB Needham (Fortune), Bates, Grey (Rama), Rapp Collins (Interact) and Dentsu Young & Rubicam. \par \par \uc2  But several local agencies, such as Subiakto Prisoedarsono's Hotline Advertising, have also distinguished themselves by creating popular and unique advertisements, Yusca said. \par \par \uc2  Cakram reported several Hotline advertisements had won a place in viewers' hearts. \par \par \uc2  Its TV commercial for Sanaflu cold medication, Belum Tahu Dia (He Doesn't Know Yet), garnered the highest total - 28.6 percent - of the more than one million votes mailed to private television station, RCTI, in a "Viewer's Choice" poll. \par \par \uc2  Another Subiakto advertisement, Xon-Cenya mana? (Where's the Xon-Ce?), for a vitamin supplement, was voted the audience favorite in a previous award program conducted by private TV station, SCTV. \par \par \uc2  Yusca said the advertising industry had focused on lucrative TV commercials since the emergence of private TV stations. \par \par \uc2  Data from Media Scene industry publication confirmed Rp 2.2 trillion was allocated for TV advertising last year. This comprised 53.2 percent of total advertising expenditures of Rp 4.1 trillion. \par \par \uc2  This year's TV advertising haul is projected to be as much as Rp 2.7 trillion, or 55.8 percent of the total. \par \par \uc2  Research \par \par \uc2  Yusca said a successful advertisement ideally involved market research to check whether the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  understood its message. \par \par \uc2  "Unfortunately, since market research is quite expensive, not all advertisers or producers are willing to carry out market research prior to launching an advertisement," he said. \par \par \uc2  Foreign or multinational companies are usually the only ones to conduct market research, Yusca said. \par \par \uc2  "They believe in the benefit of market research, while most of the local advertisers do not fully understand its gains." \par \par \uc2  The advertising industry is also feeling the pinch in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, he said. \par \par \uc2  "We are in a tougher situation since our clients will be stricter in \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  their advertising \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . They will not launch, for instance, a three-month advertising campaign, but instead opt for a shorter term campaign. \par \par \uc2  "So we have to work harder because we have to find ways that with the same amount of money, or even less, the advertising campaign can be as effective as before." \par \par \uc2  He added that monetary woes had been exacerbated because many advertising agencies here use U.S. dollars to pay their expatriate employees, production expenses and office rental fees. \par