\par\par \b \uc2  Women workers struggle to support families. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Emmy Fitri \par \uc2 914 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 December 1997\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1997 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The majority of workers in labor intensive industries are women, such as in exported textiles, footwear and factories manufacturing processed wood products. \par \par \uc2  From what the following workers say, a small increase in the regional minimum wage, if not a delay, would leave the women and their families scrambling even harder to survive. \par \par \uc2  One man, Pami Sutiono, claimed with pride that the eldest of his three daughters, Teti, was the family's backbone. \par \par \uc2  The 42-year-old ambulance driver said he only went home once a week and could not always bring home money. \par \par \uc2  "If I don't get an order (to drive the ambulance) I don't get paid," he said. Ambulance driving only earned him enough to live in Jakarta, he added. \par \par \uc2  "So if I get two or three orders, than I can go home and give the money to my wife," he said. \par \par \uc2  Despite such \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Pami can work with the thought that Teti's regular wage supports the family. She works in a cookie factory in Cikarang, Bekasi. \par \par \uc2  "She has worked there since she graduated from \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  high school," he said. \par \par \uc2  Teti earned at least Rp 300,000 per month and gave almost all of it to her mother, her father said. \par \par \uc2  But Pami said that he worried about Teti's health as she sometimes had to double her work hours to get overtime pay. \par \par \uc2  He also said that he was concerned how Teti could live up to her urban-like environment, where it seemed the norm for girls was to wear smart dresses and make up. \par \par \uc2  He will have more to worry about if Teti's company is among 85 firms in Bekasi asking permission to lay off workers, according to researcher Indrasari Tjandraningsih. \par \par \uc2  "Unlike most girls here, my daughter is very plain and modest," he said. \par \par \uc2  Zuraida, who hails from Ciawi, West Java, cannot afford to even to think about lipstick and clothes. \par \par \uc2  The eldest of five of a peasant couple, she said she had to save at least half her earnings to send home any money. \par \par \uc2  "But the money I send now barely has the same value that it used to have." \par \par \uc2  In the past, the money Zuraida earned could be used to buy fertilizer and to pay for her brothers and sisters' school fees. \par \par \uc2  "Last week when I went home, my father said the price of fertilizer increased while the supply was limited, so he had to rush to buy it, otherwise we wouldn't be able to grow our rice," she said. \par \par \uc2  Almost half of the Rp 200,000 she sends home is spent on fertilizer. \par \par \uc2  New Year \par \par \uc2  Zuraida said she did not want to think about the approaching holidays of Christmas, New Year's, the Ramadhan fasting month and Idul Fitri. \par \par \uc2  She usually sets aside money for her parents to buy her younger siblings dresses and extra food. \par \par \uc2  "Even the price of tempeh has increased. If I have the money I'll shop for my parents, but if I don't why should I push myself too hard?" she said. \par \par \uc2  Kartini, who had worked at a shoe factory for five years in the Pulo Gadung industrial area, East Jakarta, said she did not understand all the fuss on television and in newspapers. \par \par \uc2  "I'd rather read a novel or a comic book," she said. \par \par \uc2  "I know they're talking about economics and the future of the country but it's better for me to work harder so I can be promoted with a higher salary," Kartini said with conviction. \par \par \uc2  She said she could not send any money home. \par \par \uc2  Of her earnings, "I save in case I want to go home" to Madiun, East Java. She is also more mindful of her personal needs. \par \par \uc2  "My salary is only enough for living here; it's not much but I can afford some entertainment and a few new dresses," she said. \par \par \uc2  She adds, "I like to buy lipstick, usually I buy one for less than Rp 15,000 and stroll around Arion Plaza (in East Jakarta), sometimes just to window shop with my friends." \par \par \uc2  The Ramadhan fasting month, she said, was an opportunity to be frugal. \par \par \uc2  While housewives felt they needed to spend more to satisfy the family's appetite at the dawn breakfast and breaking of the fast, Kartini said, "I'll be able to save because I don't eat as much." \par \par \uc2  She said she would be very happy if the regional minimum wage was raised, keeping with the tradition of the strict \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Minister of Manpower Abdul Latief. \par \par \uc2  Kartini may not have heard of employers' warnings that they may not be able to live up to the annual expectation. \par \par \uc2  But she knows this Idul Fitri is no time for the usual showering of gifts of love. The annual bonus which she and her colleagues have received would only be enough for the bus fare home. \par \par \uc2  "I figure that as usual the bus fare and food prices will go up, so I will not be able to bring along souvenirs for my family," she said. \par \par \uc2  She said when she gets her monthly wage of Rp 180,000, she first allocates part of it for the rent shared with five women, also from Madiun. \par \par \uc2  The monthly rent for rooms near the factory, simply divided into two with a piece of plywood, ranges from Rp 80,000 to Rp 200,000. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1997 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011001dtcl003gf\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
